---
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";
import Docs from "../../layouts/Docs.astro";

const synopsis = `trellis changelog new [--package <pkg>] --kind <kind> --body <text>
trellis changelog check --base <ref> [--head <ref>] [--json]
trellis version plan [--json]
trellis version apply [--json]`;

const fragment = `project = "lat_core"
kind = "Added"
body = "Add graph-parallel task scheduling"`;

const newExample = `$ trellis changelog new --package lat_core --kind Fixed \\
    --body "Reject path deps that escape the workspace"
created .changes/unreleased/lat_core-1.toml`;

const checkJson = `{
  "has-entries": true,
  "needs-entry": true,
  "invalid-fragments": [],
  "packages": [
    { "name": "lat_core", "changed": true, "has-entry": true, "fragments": 2 },
    { "name": "lat_cli", "changed": true, "has-entry": false, "fragments": 0 }
  ],
  "preview": "| package | status |\\n| --- | --- |\\n…"
}`;

const planOutput = `$ trellis version plan
lat_core: 1.1.0 -> 1.2.0 (2 fragment(s))
lat_cli: 0.4.2 -> 0.4.3 (1 fragment(s))`;
---

<Docs
  title="Changelog & versioning — Trellis docs"
  description="Trellis has a native changelog engine: TOML fragments in .changes/unreleased/, version bumps derived from their kinds, changelogs assembled from rendered sections."
>
  <h1>Changelog &amp; versioning</h1>
  <p>
    The changelog engine is native — no second tool to install in CI, no config
    file to keep in sync with the workspace. Changes are recorded as small TOML
    fragments; version bumps and changelog sections are derived from them.
  </p>

  <Code lang="txt" code={synopsis} />

  <h2>Fragments</h2>
  <p>
    A fragment is one file in <code>.changes/unreleased/</code> with three
    keys — the package it belongs to, a configured change kind, and the entry
    text:
  </p>
  <Code lang="toml" title=".changes/unreleased/lat_core-1.toml" code={fragment} />
  <p>
    <code>changelog new</code> writes one non-interactively —
    <code>--kind</code> and <code>--body</code> are explicit flags, which suits
    CI and agents as well as shells (<code>--package</code> can be omitted when
    the workspace has exactly one releasable package):
  </p>
  <Code lang="console" code={newExample} />

  <div class="callout">
    <p>
      Invalid fragments — unknown package or kind, empty body, unparseable
      TOML — are hard errors for <code>check</code>, <code>plan</code>, and
      <code>apply</code>, and <code>doctor</code> flags them on every PR.
      Silently dropping a change is exactly the drift trellis exists to
      prevent.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Enforcing entries on PRs</h2>
  <p>
    <code>changelog check</code> maps a <code>base...head</code> diff to
    packages and fails (non-zero exit) if a changed releasable package has no
    unreleased fragment. <code>--json</code> emits a payload — including a
    markdown <code>preview</code> — ready for a PR sticky comment:
  </p>
  <Code lang="json" code={checkJson} />

  <h2>Planning a release</h2>
  <p>
    <code>version plan</code> is the dry run: each pending package's next
    version, computed from its fragments' kinds. The largest bump among a
    package's fragments wins; kinds and the bump each implies are configurable
    under
    <a href="/docs/configuration/">
      <code>[tools.trellis.changelog]</code></a>.
  </p>
  <Code lang="console" code={planOutput} />

  <h2>Applying it</h2>
  <p><code>version apply</code> performs the release bookkeeping in one step. Per pending package, it:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Renders the new version section from the fragments (minijinja templates,
      configurable) and stores it under <code>.changes/&lt;package&gt;/</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Reassembles the package's <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> from its stored
      sections, newest first.
    </li>
    <li>
      Bumps the version in <code>gleam.toml</code> with a surgical TOML edit —
      no regex, formatting preserved.
    </li>
    <li>
      Patches every member's <code>manifest.toml</code> so locked
      workspace-internal dependencies match the new versions.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The whole operation makes <strong>zero Hex network calls</strong> — that
    constraint is load-bearing, because running <code>gleam update</code> per
    package trips Hex rate limits on shared CI runners.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>
      Each package's <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> is a generated file: the source
      of truth is the version sections under
      <code>.changes/&lt;package&gt;/</code>, and <code>apply</code>
      reassembles the changelog from them.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    From here, <a href="/docs/publishing/">publishing</a> covers turning
    pending fragments into a release PR (<code>trellis release pr</code>), tags,
    and Hex publishes.
  </p>
</Docs>
